                <div class="kicker"><span class="kicker"><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/recess">RECESS</a></span></div>

                <h1>Lazar takes break from Broadway to visit alma mater</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/7bd4b3a0-49ed-4c9f-861c-bdfb315140fc.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="" class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            

                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/paul-horak">Paul Horak</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">April 1, 2010 | 4:00am EDT</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2010/04/lazar-takes-break-broadway-visit-alma-mater" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2010/04/lazar-takes-break-broadway-visit-alma-mater&amp;text=Lazar takes break from Broadway to visit alma mater" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Lazar%20takes%20break%20from%20Broadway%20to%20visit%20alma%20mater%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2010%2F04%2Flazar-takes-break-broadway-visit-alma-mater" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>On his day off, Broadway talent Aaron Lazar will trade the towering steel structures of busy New York for the flower-filled lanes of Duke.</p>
<p>It will be the Trinity &rsquo;98 grad&rsquo;s first time back at his alma mater since his five-year reunion. In addition to spending time with former friends and professors and stopping to take in the welcome warm weather, he will also be giving a theater master class open to everyone.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>The master class, to take place Monday evening, is a chance for serious theater students to get one-on-one time with an industry talent at the pinnacle of his profession. Lazar will share the expertise and insight he has gained from his experiences in the Mecca of theater with students who may be considering following in his footsteps.</p>
<p>After graduating from Duke, Lazar went on to study at the College-Conservatory of Music at the University of Cincinnati. Over the past 10 years, he has been a part of numerous musicals including <em>Les Miserables</em>, <em>South Pacific</em> and currently <em>A Little Night Music</em>.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The best thing has been exploring and working with people across the world, never knowing when the phone will ring and who will be on the other end,&rdquo; Lazar said.</p>
<p>In fact, there were plans to bring Lazar to Duke last semester, although they had to be scrapped when he got a call from the producers of<em> A Little Night Music</em>. In the play, Lazar assumes the role of Count Carl-Magnus Malcolm alongside Broadway newcomer Catherine Zeta Jones and the venerable Angela Lansbury, who is 84.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I like characters that are well written, and I generally play &lsquo;privileged&rsquo; characters&mdash;often aristocrats and such,&rdquo; Lazar said.</p>
<p>It is indeed a privilege to have Lazar come to Duke. Contrary to some popular belief, the lives of professional Broadway actors and actresses are extremely busy.&nbsp;</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Eight shows a week, six days a week, three hours a show. Take into account the rehearsals and pre-show preparations and you easily see a workload total of more than 40 hours a week.&nbsp;</p>
<p>But it wasn&rsquo;t Lazar&rsquo;s busy schedule that was keeping him from coming to Duke&mdash;it was finances. Senior Margaret Skoglund is one of the people most responsible for Lazar&rsquo;s visit.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It was like torture trying to find funds,&rdquo; Skoglund said. &ldquo;But eventually things fell into place and we were able to agree on a date and get the backing of a lot of interested and supportive people and organizations.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Skoglund first met Lazar last summer in a small New York City diner.&nbsp; She is interested in one day becoming a theater producer, the person responsible for managing industry talents like Lazar.</p>
                            

<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="fdab49f43c">
